{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> χρῡσίον</b>, τό, <br /> <i>diminutive</i> of χρυσός, <b>a piece of gold,</b> generally, <b>gold,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.95, 97, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Euthydemus” 288e, “R.” 336e, +others \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>anything made of gold, gold plate, ornaments of gold,</b> etc., ἄσημον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.13: _plural_, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 27.10, 48.55, 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus “Σαμία” 167, NT.1Pet.3.3, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Timoleon” 15. \">NT+5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> especially <b>gold coin, money,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Cyclops” 161; οὔτ᾽ ἀργύριον οὔτε χρυσίον 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 472, compare “Pl.” 808, “Ra.” 720 (troch.), etc.; χ. Ἀττικόν “IG” 22.1687.16; λῆρος πάντα πρὸς τὸ χ. 4th c.BC: Antiphanes Comicus 232.1; ἐγὼ δ᾽ ὑπέλαβον χρησίμους εἶναι θεοὺς τἀργύριον καὶ τὸ χ. 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus 537.4: but στατῆρας χρυσίου 5th c.BC: Eupolis Comicus 112; χρυσία \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<b>pieces of gold,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 336e. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> <b>gold thread,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ ἄρθρων ἐμβολῆς” 32. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> as a term of endearment, <b>my little treasure!</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 930, compare “Ap” 11.232 (Callias argument). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> ={τὸ τῶν παιδίων αἰδοῖον}, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.AD(?): Hesychius Legal icographus \">Refs 5th c.AD+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5553","accentedUnicode":"χρυσίο